       Change Summary Explanation
       The FY 2026 President's Budget submission did not reflect FY 2027 through FY 2030 funding. Therefore, an explanation of the change between the two budget
       positions for FY 2027 cannot be made in a relevant manner.

       FY 2025 decreases between the Previous President's Budget and Current President's Budget by 32.394 million due to adjustments for other United States Space
       Force priorities and by 15.821 million for Small Business Innovation Research (SBIR) and Small Business Technology Transfer (STTR) program allocation.

       FY 2026 increases between the Previous President's Budget and Current President's Budget by 25.534 million due to 42.500 million of Congressional adds
       (Defense of Low Earth Orbit Satellites, L-Band Phased Array Demonstration, Real Aperture Radar Technologies, Situational Awareness Solutions, Transport
       Layer Software Architecture) and a 6.966 million reduction for Section 8151 SBIR reduction.

       FY 2027 decreases from FY 2026 by 181.785 million due to adjustments for other United States Space Force priorities. The FY 2027 funds will continue to
       support risk reduction activities, demonstrations, and experiments for the PWSA.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                            FY 2025     FY 2026      FY 2027
Title: Space Development Agency R&E                                                                                                              379.182     453.023      313.738
Description: Research and development activities to support development, demonstration, and fielding of a resilient military
sensing and data transport capability via a proliferated space architecture in Low Earth Orbit (LEO). The funds support the
development of an increasingly broad set of technologies (including alternative navigation solutions, advanced missile tracking,
intelligence signal fusion algorithms, integrated battle management algorithms, advanced optical communications, and next
generation tactical data links) that are critical to delivering a robust initial warfighting capability in the Proliferated Warfighter Space
Architecture (PWSA).

FY 2026 Plans:
Tranche 0
- Continue to conduct post-Capstone demonstrations and experimentations with warfighters.
- Begin end-of-life operations on select satellites.

Tranche 1
- Resolve anomalous behavior in system interoperability and compatibility, including optical communications, space-to-ground
radio frequency (RF), Link 16, and Networking.
- Continue mission engineering support activities including Concept of Operations (CONOPS) and Concept of Employment
(CONEMP) development, user segment integration, developmental and operational test planning, and characterization and
modeling of system performance targeting advanced use case capabilities.
- Augment User Guides and Interface Control Documents (ICDs) and conduct integration and test activities to onboard additional
Transport mission partners.

Tranche 2
- Support risk reduction of Transport Layer Tranche 2 (TLT2) satellites, ground systems, and integration.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
- Continue interoperability and compatibility testing for key T2 interfaces including optical communications, space-to-ground radio
frequency (RF), Link 16, tactical satellite communications (TACSATCOM), Integrated Broadcast Service - Low Earth Orbit (IBS-L),
and Networking and Encryption.
- Continue mission engineering support activities including Concept of Operations (CONOPS) and Concept of Employment
(CONEMP) development, user segment integration, developmental and operational test planning, and characterization and
modeling of system performance.
- Continue development of user Interface Control Documents (ICDs).
- Fund mission unique hardware and integration of the T2 space vehicles on the National Security Space Launch (NSSL) Launch
vehicles.

Tranche 3
- Expand Ground Entry Point (GEP) global footprint in preparation for launch of Tranche 3 (T3) space vehicles.
- Continue development of the PWSA Ground Segment in support of T3.
- Initiate PWSA ground segment evolution, enhancing PWSA framework capabilities for future Tranches.

Risk Reduction Activities
- Continue to conduct analysis, pursue tech maturation initiatives, and apply lessons learned to inform on-going and future
development and delivery activities for data transport at the tactical edge.

Tranche x Demonstration and Experimentation System (TxDES)
- Demonstrate and advance the PWSA architecture and its components to fill existing and future gaps to support warfighting
capabilities in Missile Warning, Missile Tracking and Missile Defense. The program provides rapid 2-year sprints supporting
vendor development, technology maturation and risk reduction in both government-dedicated and commercial connected
capabilities. Projects may include:
• Proliferated Warfighter Space Architecture (PWSA) integration with proliferated Low Earth Orbit Space Data Network (SDN)
• Development of new sensor technology for Tranche 3+
• Acceleration of PWSA integration into Current Missions (Battle Management Command, Control, and Communications (BMC3)
across the kill chain)
• Development of enhanced tipping and queuing sensors for Combat ID
• Deorbit as a Service for proliferated constellation maintenance
• PNT over communication channels, PNT SA payload upgrades and light weight PNT signal demonstrations to support user
integration prior to operations

Advanced Fire Control (AFC)

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2025    FY 2026      FY 2027
- Perform integration testing between Fire-control On Orbit-support-to-the-war (FOO) Fighter and the Demonstration Operations
Center (DOC).
- Continue Advanced Fire Control Ground Infrastructure (AFCGI) effort to provide a common, enduring ground infrastructure and
resources to minimize cost and complexity for fire-control-related space vehicle demonstration and experimentation programs
(beginning with FOO Fighter).
- Continue execution of other advanced fire control efforts including Warlock and Goliath.
- Complete network design for Operational AFC.

Other activities in this line may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation,
etc.
