C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                             FY 2025      FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Electro-Optical/Infrared Weather System (EWS)                                                                               66.967       69.777        68.979
Description: EWS will focus on an overlapping multi-phased approach intended to mature multi-spectral imaging capabilities
to collect and disseminate terrestrial atmospheric phenomena to support Department of War (DoW) operations. Primary effort

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
will focus on competitive prototyping of the latest industry sensor and bus designs, development, integration, test, launch and
successful on-orbit demonstrations. This effort will also assess current industrial capability to deliver Cloud Characterization (CC)
and Theatre Weather Imagery (TWI) data in a viable commercial service business, hosted on a proliferated Low Earth Orbit (LEO)
mesh network. Program will minimize technology maturity risks by evaluating multiple, competitive Electro-optical/infrared (EO/IR)
sensors, satellite vehicle prototypes and commercial services in order to inform a decision on a cost-effective system or service
to replace the legacy Defense Meteorological Satellite Program (DMSP) constellation in a timely manner. Per the approved EWS
Acquisition Strategy, the Program Office will continue to competitively prototype sensor and bus designs for a LEO architecture to
replace DMSP constellation, while leveraging the existing SBEM Family of Systems (Phase II) to meet required data refresh rate
for the DoW.

FY 2026 Plans:
Conduct Operational Demonstration #1 pre-ship review ahead of shipment of completed space vehicle to payload processing
facility for launch processing. Support launch and on-orbit checkout of General Atomics Ops Demo #1, characterizing its
performance to provide ops-quality data, meet space-based Environmental Monitoring (SBEM) Electro-optical/infrared (EO/IR)
requirements for Cloud Characterization and Theater Weather Imagery, while informing SBEM acquisition strategy for fielding
full operational systems. Fund small launch vehicle through RSLP OSP-4 contract to support Ops Demo #2 launch, currently
slated for FY28, and provide support for Ops Demo #2 space vehicle to launch vehicle integration study. Continue to invest for
the development of commercial capabilities to address full SBEM Gap requirements and Phase III activities. Develop options for
remote ground station to support future Geostationary (GEO) for persistent EO/IR coverage of Indian Ocean region.

Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction,
prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond
to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2027 Plans:
Conduct Operational Demonstration #1 pre-ship review ahead of shipment of completed space vehicle to payload processing
facility for launch base processing. Support launch and on-orbit checkout of General Atomics Ops Demo #1, characterizing
its performance to provide ops-quality data, meet Department of War (DoW) Environmental Monitoring (EM) Electro-optical/
infrared (EO/IR) requirements for Cloud Characterization and Theater Weather Imagery, while informing overall EM Mission
Area Acquisition Framework (MAAF) strategy for fielding full EO/IR operational systems. Initiate Operational Demonstration #2
space vehicle build. Conduct delta design activities and begin build, integration and test. Fund small launch vehicle through RSLP
OSP-4 contract to support Ops Demo #2 launch in FY28, and provide support for Ops Demo #2 space vehicle to launch vehicle
integration study.

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                    FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027

Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction,
prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond
to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility. In FY 2027, MUON, Space-Based Environmental Monitoring
transfers to the newly established 'EM Data as a Service' major thrust.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 net increase of $0.798M includes funding to enable the Operational Demonstration #2 space vehicle build and the
outgoing transfer of Muon SBEM to the 'EM Data as a Service' major thrust.
Title: EM Data as a Service                                                                                                                  -        0.000         37.515
Description: Environmental Monitoring Data as a Service (EM Daas) is not a new start and was previously funded within the
EWS major thrust of this program element. The EM DaaS Acquisition Strategy is built around the EM Mission Area Acquisition
Framework (MAAF) which is a mission engineering process for prioritizing validated requirements, identifying capability gaps
based on the civil and international Family of Systems, and leverages non-materiel solutions and commercial EM data buys before
building dedicated Space Force-owned systems. The EM Daas effort matures commercial EM technologies through on-orbit
demonstrations and forecaster assessments to meet validated Department of War (DoW) EM requirements and will augment or
replace legacy space-based EM systems. This program includes commercial system development, on-orbit deployment, testing
and assessment of emerging commercial weather concepts in addition to ground processing updates to ensure compatibility with
DoW Weather Center models.

The EM DaaS effort includes, but is not limited to direct investment in commercial EM space vehicles, commercial launch in
addition to commercial weather data buys for assessment and integration into DoW weather centers. The EM DaaS program also
procures validated data from commercial sources for operational forecaster products.

In addition to augmenting or replacing legacy EM systems, EM DaaS development and operational data procurements will meet
prioritized requirements from DoW forecasters and more rapidly fill capability gaps due to potential loss of data from civil or
international systems. The EM DaaS effort also continues the Muon SBEM variant contract. The FY 2027 Muon space-based
Environmental Monitoring (SBEM) variant satellite effort will launch two satellites for DoW weather center suitability assessment.
The EM DaaS acquires data from all EM sensor types to include Electro-optical/infrared (EO/IR), active and passive microwave,
and space weather systems.

