 global 24/7 Low Earth Orbit (LEO) coverage to meet Space-based EM weather requirements; specifically Gaps 1) Cloud Characterization (CC) and 2) Theatre Weather
 Imagery (TWI). This capability will operationally replace the obsolete and aging DMSP constellation, projected end-of-life Sep 2026 due to insufficient ops and
 sustainment funding for continued operations. Without the CC and TWI data, production of global predictive cloud and terrestrial weather data will be severely impacted,
 affecting daily air operations and intelligence gathering for strategic mission planning. Moreover, INDOPACOM, CENTCOM, and AFRICOM will be unable to forecast
 and monitor adverse weather conditions over eastern Africa and the Indian Ocean. Lastly, the US will not meet the Department of War DoW responsibility of maintaining
 the SBEM civil/international partnership for the Family of Systems architecture without timely delivery of a LEO replacement system.

EM Data as a Service (DaaS): The EM DaaS effort matures commercial technologies through on-orbit demonstrations and integrates commercial data to meet
validated DoW requirements that will augment or replace legacy SBEM systems. The EM DaaS program will more rapidly deliver EM products from space-based
commercial sources without the long-lead times associated with traditional Government-owned systems. This program includes commercial system development,
on-orbit deployment, testing and assessment of emerging commercial weather concepts in addition to ground processing updates to ensure compatibility with DoW
Weather Center models. The EM DaaS program also procures validated data from commercial sources for operational forecaster products.

The EM DaaS effort continues the Muon SBEM variant contract previously included in the EWS Major Thrust in FY 2026. This effort involves the modification of a
commercial space vehicle line with both wildfire detection and SBEM mission capabilities in order to meet DoW requirements. The program has flexibility to provide data
from EO/ IR, passive and active microwave and space weather sensors to meet prioritized requirements based on mission needs.

Commercial Geostationary EO/IR Capabilities: The Geostationary (GEO) EO/IR capabilities provides overhead persistent TWI for near-real time weather data in the
INDOPACOM and CENTCOM Area of Responsibility (AOR) in addition to providing low latency data for CC weather models. The GEO EO/IR capabilities is a follow-
on to the EWS-G satellite system with projected end of life in 2030. The requirement for persistent GEO EO/IR coverage is necessary to meet a Global 1-hour refresh
requirement as documented in JROCM 101-24. Without the capability, operational forecasters in the INDOPACOM and CENTCOM AOR would face TWI and CC data
latency greater than the JROCM 101-24 requirement of 1 hour and result in high impacts to air, naval and ground operations. The Space Force will pursue commercial
acquisition strategies, to include commercial operations, and civil/international partnerships to provide the GEO EO/IR capabilities affordably and rapidly to prevent
a 2030 data gap in the INDOPACOM and CENTCOM AOR. Commercial GEO EO/IR capabilities also include upgrading the EWS-G Remote Ground Station with a
resilient antenna capability compatible with high data rate modern Civil GEO satellites and future Commercial GEO EO/IR satellites.

This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver EWS for weapon system capability. The use of such
program funds would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

This effort is in Budget Activity 4, Advanced Component Development and Prototypes (ACD&P), because efforts are necessary to evaluate integrated technologies,
representative modes or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.

This program falls within the Weather mission area which provides mission-critical environmental intelligence to support global military operations and delivers essential
meteorological and oceanographic data to joint forces across all domains and detects space-based environmental threats to protect vital U.S. and allied space assets.
