C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
Description: Provide space warfighters with interconnected, scalable, and distributed capabilities for full-spectrum test and
training to achieve space superiority. Includes physical and digital test ranges and mission trainers to develop, validate, and
sharpen joint warfighting capabilities necessary to enable the space superiority required to achieve peace through strength.

Supports the development of the United States Space Force (USSF) Operational Test & Training Infrastructure (OTTI) in response
to USSF prioritized requirements. Includes new capability developments required for the physical range, digital environments,
systems, tools, capabilities, and underlying physical and digital infrastructure. These capability developments are critical for
integrated testing activities, training, exercises, wargames, and tactics development for space systems.

Includes development, demonstration, and continuous delivery of test and training hardware and software identified by Space
Training & Readiness Command (STARCOM) (the USSF Operational Test Authority) to validate system performance and train the
Guardians that operate them.

Provides a safe, secure, realistic, and relevant space arena to support test and training needs. Capabilities enable Guardian and
mission system combat lethality.

LOE 1: Live/Physical Test and Training Range consists of four sub elements:

a. Cyber Range: Provides live and simulated cyber operations and security test and training. Delivers Verification, Validation, and
Accreditation (VV&A) of USSF systems to ensure cyber resiliency, security, and interoperability.

b. Electromagnetic Spectrum Operations Range: Provides ground-based system, range control, and on-orbit surrogate for
Electronic Warfare (EW), Satellite Communications (SATCOM), and Position Navigation and Timing (PNT) test and training.

c. Orbital Range: Provides sensors, data fusion, and on-orbit surrogates to enable live, on-orbit Orbital Warfare (OW) test and
training. On-orbit range system supports execution of exquisite, discrete demonstrations in the operational environment.

d. Advanced Programs: Invests in ground-based activities (i.e. hardware-in-the-loop (HWIL) chamber modifications, material
analysis, etc.) to satisfy enterprise needs associated with space superiority efforts.

LOE 2: Digital Test & Training consists of two sub elements:




