B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Ground Resilient Integration & Framework for Operational NC3 (GRIFFON)                                                                    -        0.000       519.640
Description: GRIFFON is the Ground Segment solution for ESS. It includes the ESS Ground Integration and Framework (GIF),
System of Systems Integration (SoSI), and software application development efforts. GRIFFON software applications include
mission planning, command and control (both in-band and out-of-band) along with other architecture activities required to support
the ESS Space Segment, system operators, strategic users, and Combatant Commands (COCOMs).

FY 2026 Plans:
(Project 643725 BA 04) The GRIFFON program will continue within the Execution Phase of the Software Acquisition Pathway and
will begin a critical year for integration and testing across the entire ESS architecture, to include all Ground software applications,
framework, and test sites.

Continue Maturation of the ESS ground framework and integration prototype. The GIF/SoSI vendor will define and develop the
Ground Assembly, Integration, and Test (Ground AI&T) minimum viable product (MVP) and run the integration test with all ESS
vendors and system capabilities in FY 2026, with a projected exit of Ground AI&T in FY 2027. The Ground AI&T milestone will be
the defining event that will encapsulate, integrate, and test all of ESS Ground's individual software applications and capabilities
into the system architecture. The Ground AI&T milestone is the first integration test on the road to Initial Operational Capability
(IOC), immediately preceding the next integration milestone testing of System AI&T in FY 2028. System AI&T will include testing
Ground with the Space, Crypto, and Terminal segments, and will ensure that the system is interoperable and capable to enter into
integrated launch testing.

The Mission Planning prototype will be down-selected from two to one vendor and then will be integrated with the space, crypto,
terminal, and ground framework segments. The Mission Planning prototype will then begin integrating with operational users and
building test and training applications with the GIF/SoSI vendor. All integration issues found during Ground AI&T testing will be
fixed in FY 2026 in an agile ramp up to ensure software is mission capable upon exit of Ground AI&T in FY 2027.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
The Out-of-Band Command and Control (OOB-C2) software application vendors will begin modernization of the legacy software to
integrate with the Ground framework.

The In-Band Command and Control (IB-C2) software application will begin development and testing with the Ground Framework
and other mission applications. IB-C2 will begin integration efforts and testing in an operationally relevant environment.

The ESS C2 Terminals will be modernized for cryptographic, cybersecurity, resiliency, survivability, and interoperabilty
requirements, necessary to support ESS and meet critical ground segment, space segment, and systems integration need dates.
ESS must enter Ground Assembly, Integration and Test in FY 2026 to meet the USSTRATCOM threat-driven strategic need date
by FY 2032. The production and fielding effort for C2 terminals is broken out into launch readiness, IOC requirements, and FOC
requirements, to ensure the right terminals are fielded just in time for each of those milestones. While this effort may have begun
in FY 2025, it will continue in FY 2026 with production of first articles required for launch readiness.

Continue technology maturation of multiple GRIFFON prototype demonstration contracts that will conclude with a successful exit
of Ground AI&T in FY 2027. Interoperability testing and integration patches will be developed in an agile DevSecOps pipeline to
also ensure cyber resilience is a part of delivered software. Resilient technology studies will ensure the fielded system addresses
current threat scenarios for endurance capability, command and control, mission control, and user terminal interface.

Fund prototype technology maturation, system integration, and Ground AI&T testing in order to ensure an integrated,
interoperable, secure software framework and cyber secure software delivery pipeline, software applications, and user interfaces
with the enterprise community. Further mature a development, security, and operations (DevSecOps) pipeline for software
vendors to test their applications on the ground framework to conduct end-to-end integration testing. Conduct early integration
testing at government sites. Maintain user agreements with operational sites outlining deliveries and key milestones to ensure
system functionality by FY 2029, prior to the first ESS space launch.

Conduct integration testing and connectivity with Protected SATCOM Key Management Architecture (PKMA) and cryptographic
modernization efforts with the NSA. Communicate any necessary modifications to legacy terminal programs to ensure entire
integrated system functions within modernized cyber architecture. Continue development activities in support of the ground
segment and system/mission integration schedules.

GRIFFON transitioned from BA 04 Project 643725 in FY 2026 to BA 05 Project 650015 in FY 2027
FY 2027 Plans:

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                     FY 2025    FY 2026       FY 2027
The GRIFFON program will continue efforts in the Execution Phase of the Software Acquisition Pathway for integration and testing
across the entire ESS architecture, to include the Ground software applications, framework, terminals, and test sites.

Continue maturation of the ESS ground framework and integration prototype. Complete Systems Engineering work in support of
the System-Level CDR in FY 2027. The GIF/SoSI vendor, with the program office as the lead systems integrator, will continue to
run the Ground Assembly, Integration, and Test (Ground AI&T) minimum viable product (MVP) integration test with a projected
exit of Ground AI&T in FY 2027. The Ground AI&T milestone will be the defining event that will encapsulate, integrate, and test
all of ESS GRIFFON software applications and capabilities into the system architecture. The Ground AI&T milestone is the first
integration test on the road to Initial Operational Capability (IOC)and precedes the next integration test milestone, System AI&T, in
FY 2028.

The down-selected Mission Planning (MP) application developer will continue development and integration in support of Ground
AI&T. The MP prototype releases will be integrated with space, crypto, terminal, and ground framework segments.

Continue development of the Out-of-Band Command and Control (OOB-C2) application MVP capability during the Phase 1 period
and support continued integration and testing throughout Ground AI&T. Prepare and release a solicitation for the Phase 2 OOB-
C2 application development with contract award expected in early FY 2028. Phase 2 will complete application development
through System AI&T and continue mission integration and testing through FY 2030.

The In-Band Command and Control (IB-C2) software application will continue development and integration to support Ground
AI&T testing with the Ground Framework and other mission applications throughout FY 2027. The Ground AI&T IB-C2 testing will
be performed in an operationally-relevant test environment with the, MIT-LL developed, Terminal Management Plane Emulator
(TMP-E) and System Test Terminal.

The ESS Command and Control (C2) Terminals (i.e., Family of Advanced Beyond-Line-of-Sight Terminal (FAB-T) Command Post
Terminal (CPT) will be modernized for cryptographic, cybersecurity, resiliency, survivability, and interoperability requirements,
necessary to support ESS and meet critical Ground Segment, Space Segment, and systems integration need dates, as well as the
production and fielding of 4 ESS C2 terminal pre-production units in support of Systems AI&T in FY 2028, Initial Launch Capability
(ILC), IOC, and FOC milestones.

The ESS Ground Resiliency initiative will be leveraging both existing and commercial capabilities to prototype a more robust and
effective ground architecture compared to the legacy system, utilizing IL-6/ IL-7 cloud capabilities and data transport connections.
Continue prototype maturation throughout FY 2027, as well as integration and test with software applications, framework, and
ground components during Ground AI&T.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027

Award the alternative C2 Terminals and OOB-C2 commercial efforts. Begin terminal architecture design, implementation and test
plan development. Begin prototyping the OOB-C2 Terminal application.

Complete initial integration testing and connectivity with PKMA and cryptographic modernization efforts with the NSA. Continue
development activities in support of the ground segment and system/mission integration schedules.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 funding increased due to scope of Ground AI&T activities, System-Level CDR support, concurrent ramp-up of system
level integration and test planning for Systems AI&T in FY 2028, and the production and fielding of 4 C2 Terminals.

GRIFFON transitioned from BA 04 Project 643725 in FY 2026 to BA 05 Project 650015 in FY 2027
Title: End-Cryptographic Unit (ECU)                                                                                                       -        0.000         52.200
Description: Develop and deliver the NSA-certified Aerospace Vehicle Equipment (AVE) Production Representative Article (PRA)
ECUs (e.g., KG-505) required for secure strategic communications encryption in the ESS Space Vehicle (SV) Bus, and non-flight
AVE Engineering Development Model (EDM) ECU (e.g. KI-2200) for SV Payload and Ground Operating Equipment (GOE) EDM
ECU (e.g., KG-256) in accordance with the approved ECU acquisition strategy and schedule. Bus AVE PRA ECU units, Payload
AVE EDM ECU units, and GOE EDM ECU units will be delivered as government-furnished equipment (GFE) for SV and Strategic
Test Terminal (ST2) interoperability and integration testing and validation activities.

FY 2026 Plans:
(Project 643725 BA 04) Continue the development and National Security Agency (NSA) cybersecurity certification process and
procedures for AVE and GOE ECUs for the ESS Strategic Test Terminal (ST2). Upon successful completion of the PDRs and
CDRs and development of engineering development models (EDMs) continue to execute AVE and GOE ECU contract through
the Engineering and Manufacturing Development (EMD) phase. Develop and build the first ECU production representative articles
(PRAs) for the Space Segment vendor to enable the complete manufacturing of an ESS Space Vehicle (SV). Deliver the first
PRAs to MIT-LL to support the development of the ST2. Continue to fund CCSD, University Affiliated Research Center (UARC),
and Federally Funded Research and Development Center (FFRDC) to provide program office support, planning, GFE, studies,
technical analyses and information or resources in conjunction with the ESS Space Development and Production Contract.
Continue the development to provide NSA-certified crypto solutions to support Telemetry, Tracking, and Command (TT&C),
Mission Data, Transmission Security (TRANSEC), and Communications Security (COMSEC); includes all required cyber,
resiliency, and security activities required, as well as Government support for contractor management and oversight.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Continue to assist with requirements trades, technical design approaches, threat assessment (e.g., VOLT) and mitigation
approaches, and ESS testing assets to include the test terminal. Continue coordination with NSA through the ECU Certification
process and modified-PKMA compatible cryptographic key material delivery. Continue activities and start work to modify AEHF-
based PKMA and Key Management Infrastructure (KMI) to support ESS development and testing, and ramp up of the KMI
services, protocols, and modification work required to be interoperable to fully support all ESS constellation requirements.

GRIFFON transitioned from BA 04 Project 643725 in FY 2026 to BA 05 Project 650015 in FY 2027
FY 2027 Plans:
Continue National Security Agency (NSA) cybersecurity certification process and procedures for AVE and GOE ECUs for the
ESS Space Segment and ST2. Maintain all required and appropriate Interim Authority to Test (IATT) approval letter(s) from NSA.
Deliver AVE and GOE PRAs to Space Segment and MIT- LL to support ST2 development. Begin integration support for for Space
Assembly, Integration & Testing (AI&T) events upon delivery of the AVE and GOE PRA ECUs. Continue iterative development
and delivery of software updates for the ECUs and continue to meet NSA's Crypto Modernization (CM) 2 and Security Evaluation
Requirements Document (SERD) 2.0 requirements. With assistance from NSA, CCSD, and MIT/LL, plan for and conduct AVE
and GOE ECU design verification, qualification, and acceptance milestones. Submit TEMPEST test plan to NSA, then begin
TEMPEST testing. Conduct Functional Configuration Audit (FCA) and Physical Configuration Audit (PCA) and provide complete
FCA and PCA data and artifacts packages to NSA and CCSD.

Continue modification of the AEHF PKMA and KMI services and protocols to support ESS capabilities and features. Deliver
cryptographic key material (Keys) and PKMA development equipment to support ECU Security Verification Testing and Space
AI&T. Continue coordination with NSA through the ECU certification process and cryptographic key material delivery.

Continue to fund CCSD, UARC, and FFRDC to provide program office support, planning, GFE, studies, technical analyses and
information or resources in conjunction with the ESS Space Development and Production Contract. Continue the development
to provide NSA-certified crypto solutions to support TT&C, Mission Data, TRANSEC, and COMSEC; includes all required
cybersecurity, resiliency, and program protection activities, as well as Government support for contractor management and
oversight. Continue to assist with requirements trades, technical design, threat assessment and mitigation strategies, and ESS
testing assets to include the test terminal.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 increased due to start of various NSA cybersecurity certification activities (SVT, TEMPEST testing, EMI/EMC testing,
FCA/PRA, etc.) for the AVE and GOE ECU units along with ST2 interoperability testing with the delivery of GOE EDM ECU units
to MIT/LL. In addition, modified PKMA test vectors/keys such as the M-keys (Maintenance Keys) will be formulated, verified, and

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
validated through collaboration amongst CCSD, GOE ECU vendor, and NSA to perform preliminary interrogability testing of the
GOE EDM and ST2 emulators.

ECU transitioned from BA 04 Project 643725 in FY 2026 to BA 05 Project 650015 in FY 2027
                                                                               Accomplishments/Planned Programs Subtotals                     -        0.000       571.840$$, $$$$, $$GRIFFON is the ground segment solution for ESS, and it includes ESS GIF, SoSI, and Software Application development efforts. The GIF will scope and provide
advisory services on the ground system infrastructure to provide a software architecture and support the corresponding software factory. The GIF contractor will provide
continual test and delivery services of the DevSecOps pipeline and software from different development and pre-production environments. It will also ensure NC3
compliance. The System Integrator will ensure all ESS segments operate cohesively to deliver interoperable capability. The SoSI will facilitate requirement verification,
validation, and sell-off to maintain an authoritative source of truth throughout the system integration process. Mission unique capability will be provided by software
applications.

In June 2022, the SAE approved the use of Department of War Instruction (DoWI) 5000.87 Software Acquisition Pathway for the GRIFFON Ground Segment. This
pathway will be used to design and develop a software-intensive ground system to promote agile software development, control program timelines, cost, and foster
innovation that is needed for resilient NC3 systems. The ESS Ground Segment awarded two 18-month competitive contracts in FY 2023 for the GIF and SoSI
prototypes. There was a down-select to one Framework and Integration prototype vendor in May 2024. The Strategic Mission Planning Applications were competitively
awarded Phase-1 to five contractor teams in September 2024 for a 6-month software demonstration. In April 2025, two of the five prototypes were continued into a 14-
month Phase-2 competition.

In November 2023, the SAE approved the acquisition strategy for the In-Band C2 software application. The In-Band C2 application was included in the ESS Space RFP
and will be completed under that contract. In June 2024, the SAE approved the acquisition strategy for the remainder of the Planning Phase for Mission Planning and
Command and Control elements, as well as Phase-2 for GIF/SoSI that will culminate at the finalization of Ground AI&T. In June 2025, the remaining application

acquisition strategies were approved by the SAE and the GRIFFON program was approved to transition from the Planning Phase to the Execution Phase of the Software
Acquisition Pathway.

An ECU acquisition strategy was approved as an ACAT III program by the Program Executive Officer (PEO) in FY 2021. The ESS program office partnered with the
Air Force Life Cycle Management Center CCSD for ECU crypto development, both on the space vehicle for payload and bus cryptographic devices and in the test
terminal. Using a CCSD-led competitive RFP, a contract for payload and payload test terminal ECU development was awarded in 1st Quarter FY 2024. The program
also partners with CCSD and the NSA to modernize and integrate the PKMA for ESS.

